Average price of stocks is not coming properly when there is sale and purchase for that stock is multiple times.
Its averaging from starting value. 
Suppose there is 1000 shares of INTC we sold 100, 120 two occasions and then purchased 200 and 250 again with higher prices. In this case it should be 1000-100=900 then 900-120= 780, calculate average price  over 780. After this 780+ 200=980 its average then  add 980+250=1230, then again take average. Curently its taking simple average which is not fulfilling the purpose by giving wrong average.

The video is really good but i have found a major problem .
The way u are calculating weighted average is completely wrong as u are considering all the buy(history!D:D>0) from the history tab and not considering that some stock might have been sold and the average price depends on the sold stocks as well .
eg :

you buy stock A at 200 of 2 qty so avg =100
later u will sell 1 stock at 150 so avg =100 (bcoz we havent invested any money yet)
later u decide to buy another at 200 so avg = (1*100+1*200)/2 = 150
but what u will get the way u are doing is (2*100+1*200)/3 = 133.33

so Purchase price in position tab is completely wrong . But all other logics are right. It would be great if u fix that or reply how u would fix this issue.

Hey this was an excellent video, thank you so much for uploading it! I made a few small changes to the formatting and one thing that you may prefer doing in the future is adding an x- and y-axis to the price chart on the dashboard. It's pretty easy to do using google finance data. 

Take the formula that you use to generate the sparklines plot and create a 5th sheet (I labeled mine "Selected Google Finance Data"). Paste the formula into the first cell and it will automatically populate the first two cells of each row with the closing price and date for the entire year. This data can then be used to generate a Closing price vs. Date chart for your security of interest. Copy and paste the new chart onto the dashboard and you're good to go. Since you're referencing the ticker symbol in cell J1, it will automatically update just like a sparklines plot would but now you'll have labeled axes to get a sense of scale for the price change over time. Thanks again!

Thank so much for video....one bug  noticed in weighted average calculation is , when you are calculating purchase price of any stock you are only considering the buy instances by ignoring how many  shares u have sold at what price. suppose you take tgt stock, first instant you have purchased 10 shares of tgt stock at 100 and u sold 2 shares at 120 and again u have added 10 more shares of   tgt stock at 200, now if you calculate weighted average ,purchase value is 150 , in this example if you have sold 2 or 8 shares  at 120 before adding 10 more stocks at 200 price  will  not have any impact on weighted average value. Kindly help to derive the actual purchase value of any stock by considering the both buy and sell instances.

you could make the MyPortfolio(History!B3:B1000, History!D3:D1000) easier by making them named ranges. Select B3:B1000, look in the top left of the sheet (should say B3:B1000; next to the formula bar) type in something like HistorySecurity (don't use spaces) and then the same for D3:D1000, name it like HistoryQuant. Then the formula would look like this =MyPortfolio(HistorySecruity,HistoryQuant). Just throwing it out there, named ranges can make things quicker and easier.

@everything money The debt question gets tricky. Debt lowers taxes so OPAT increases, meanwhile risk to financial distress also increases.  There tends to be an upside down parabolic relationship to debt and value.
As leverage increases from 0 to L‚Äô value increases. Moving past L‚Äô and value tends to go back down. 
The median US firm has L‚Äô at 30%.
Should be noted not all firms have the same optimal leverage. Cash flow volatility, tangibility of assets, size, profitability and Market to book ratios all effect L‚Äô.

Regarding Moe's question about companies always having debt - here is something I found:-

Having some debt helps to keep more of the profit in the company instead of paying in taxes. Debt is also better in some cases when the company don't want to increase stakeholder in the establishment through stocks. Once the debt is paid, no need to worry about sharing the profits with outside partners. When comes to reinvesting in the business debt provides leverage that expands the operation much faster rate than equity. Mostly for these reasons debts are structured in all operation's finance.

Google (Alphabet) is an amazing stock to buy, in my opinion, for these reasons:
1.	Strong revenue growth with an expected growth of 23.9% for 2021
2.	Low forward P/E ratio of 26, considering it continues to have double digit revenue growth
3.	The market for Google search, YouTube and Google Cloud will continue to have strong growth, in my opinion, as Google search seems to be essential in almost every aspect of life.  YouTube also continues to produce top quality content for every niche category you can think of and will help eliminate cable in conjunction with Netflix, in my opinion.
4.	Alphabet‚Äôs financial statements are incredible with strong revenue growth 12.77% in 2020 even when it was in a worst-case scenario with lockdowns and reduced advertising budgets.  Google‚Äôs paid clicks for advertising was up 19% in and impressions were up 15% in 2020.  
5.	The company is highly profitable and has an incredible balance sheet with $136.7 billion of cash and marketable securities.
6.	Alphabet stock seems like such a safe investment, in my opinion, compared to many other high flying tech stocks trading at 50+ forward P/E ratios.  I sleep very well at night holding Alphabet in my stock portfolio.

As with every company, Google stock also has some risks.  There is a risk of government intervention on how Google collects and uses its customers data and there is a risk the government may try to break up the company which I believe is unlikely to happen.

Over the last 50 years, the average PE for companies in the S&P 500 is 19.4, and over the last 30 years it is about 24. PE is highly correlated to Interest rates, which have averaged about 2.6% over the last 30 years, and been below 5% for 77% of that time. Even if rates were to rise to about 3.5% long term, I would expect a 22ish PE to be reasonable given a regression analysis I did. 

If you use a 22 PE for Google and your other assumptions stay the same, GOOG looks close to fair value (maybe a touch over-valued). I'd be a strong buyer under 2600!

I would highly recommend you update your baseline for what P/E to use. Would be happy to share this data with you, as I think it would help make for more accurate stock analysis.
@Hamsohbat totally agree!

@The Fishing Nomad I GUARANTEE he does not look at interest rates. And I don't think you should in the short term. However, in the long term, we are likely never going back to interest rates of 20% like in the 80s, when the average PE was 10. I would expect "normalized" PEs to be 18-25 in the future. I personally use 22 as the average, which is actually lower than the S&P500 PE over the last 30 years.

@The Fishing Nomad I agree you should have a margin of safety, but using 14 is about at least a 30% buffer. As well, I find he uses pretty conservative numbers as it is (8% growth despite it having grown 19% per year over the last 10 years,). I prefer to use accurate numbers, and then work the buffer in afterwards. Again, it's about being able to have a bit of a margin of safety, but not such a big one that you never invest in great companies if the value is close.
@Hamsohbat I don't think he looks at the interest rate at all when determine the PE.

Hi, I would like to start off by saying great video. I just thought I would mention as it is important and will effect the stock prices for british stocks on the database. The british stocks listed on google finance and yahoo finance use the currency GBX or GBp (Great British Pence) which is in pence as opposed to pounds. Essentially this means that in the document the value of the british stocks will be calculated incorrectly by a factor of 100. Due to them being taken as GBP instead of GBX or GBp. For examply your Rolls Royce RR.L holding is valued at ¬£102.95 per share but that price is actually in pence so in reality it should be ¬£1.0295 per share.

Paul has a fundamental misunderstanding of macroeconomics. One of the reasons why people are willing to pay 30 P/E for a fast growing tech company, is that treasuries - which currently pay about 2% - are essentially 50 P/E (2% interest rate). So you can buy Google at 30 P/E, Treasuries at 50 P/E, or hold cash and get hammered annually by inflation. It‚Äôs not that the market is irrational, it‚Äôs that the other investment alternatives (cash, bonds) have higher P/Es.

Historical P/E ratios were lower, because interest rates used to be much higher. The P/E the market will accept, has ALWAYS been partially a consequence of interest rate.

So unless you think treasury interest rates are going to triple to 6% (16 P/E) within the next seven years, Google at 12 P/E is a stretch.

Hey Cameron, amazing content as always. Could you check out Royalty Pharma ($RPRX)? It has a unique business model being in the pharmaceutical sector, where they invest into receiving royalties of various drugs that pharma companies sell. I watched the video on BMY, and one point you raised was that, certain drugs sometimes fail to get FDA approval which is why we should look for higher IRR when investing in these companies. Royalty Pharma most of the times, invests in already approved and growing drugs and receives royalty payments on it for the life of the patent, thus reducing the risk of failure and also no risk of any lawsuits later on, should the drug unfortunately have any adverse side effects even after approval. The advantage for the pharma companies is that they can then take that money and invest it into research for their next drug. And as for royalty pharma, it gets a diversified exposure to the various drugs sold by these pharma companies. It's a win win for both!

I use the spreadsheet and I made a few adjustments for myself:
-I added a Drip shares column to separate the shares I bought vs the ones I gained through DRIP re-investment. (Personally, I do not count the drip shares into Book Value, just Market Value)
-I added a Quarterly Dividend Column and an Estimated Drip shares per Quarter (helps to visualize the benefits when the share price drops)
-I added a high-water mark for Total Market Value (I like to track how high my investments have gotten to historically)
-I modified the market value with *GOOGLEFINANCE("CURRENCY:USDCAD") for my USD stocks to get an accurate impact of exchange rate fluctuations.
-I incorporated my fees into my adjusted Average Cost per shares
-I added a new Category for myself called "Contrarian" for any very low or negative beta stocks I hold (I like to keep 15% of my portfolio in stuff that moves in the opposite direction of the market like Kirkland Lake Gold or Loblaws)

@deepak pareek books are not a good media for teaching Spreadsheet. video is by far 10 times better. Just search GoogleSheets on Youtube you should have more than enough to learn. In the last decade, I have learnt from scratch in building website simply by watching youtube. And of course it depends on your luck in running into a good video matching your needs. However, YouTube is by far the most effective learning tool for me in the last decade.

The key challenge in learning spreadsheet is the complicated wrapping of functions within functions. They way I develop the spreadsheets as shown in this video is my long tried method in developing complex formula by copy and pasting the formula within another formula. It helps to break a very complex logic into smaller chunks.

If you can handle what I have shown in this video, it's likely that you are already a very advance user.  If you understand but cannot apply it on your own idea, it's likely that you need to "try to do it" so many times that one day it just "click" in your brain.

This is how I learnt anyway, through years of trial-and-error.

‚Äã@deepak pareek yes. Sounds like a logical step. It will be a complex combo of index(), match(), max() and googlefinance(). The most complex part is to get the date of the candle you are hunting for. Once you have the date, the rest of the CMP comparison will be simple.

@Stan Suen Step 1  Say find Highest volumes candle of 100 days say it is March 16, 2021. Step 2  Find the stock price range High and  Low of said day. Range of stock on march 16 is 100 to 105. Step 3  Compare the current stock price with Range. If the stock is above 105 it is bullish, If below 100 is it bearish. If between 100 to105 it is neutral.

@deepak pareek Ok. The whole thing is just to match the date using match() to find the index( like a row) within the range and  then use GoogleFinance to find the OHLC data of that specific date. then you can comparison with current price from Google Finance.

@Stan Suen CMP is current market price. suppose the highest volumes candle of last 100 days happened on say 17thMarch 2021 and that day stock was between 100 to 105. Now on say 5th april 2021, the stock closed above the 105. so it is bullish stock. so basically comparision of current market price of stock and higher volumes candle range gives the stock view.

Google (Alphabet) is an amazing stock to buy, in my opinion, for these reasons:
1.	Strong revenue growth with an expected growth of 23.9% for 2021
2.	Low forward P/E ratio of 26, considering it continues to have double digit revenue growth
3.	The market for Google search, YouTube and Google Cloud will continue to have strong growth, in my opinion, as Google search seems to be essential in almost every aspect of life.  YouTube also continues to produce top quality content for every niche category you can think of and will help eliminate cable in conjunction with Netflix, in my opinion.
4.	Alphabet‚Äôs financial statements are incredible with strong revenue growth 12.77% in 2020 even when it was in a worst-case scenario with lockdowns and reduced advertising budgets.  Google‚Äôs paid clicks for advertising was up 19% in and impressions were up 15% in 2020.  
5.	The company is highly profitable and has an incredible balance sheet with $136.7 billion of cash and marketable securities.
6.	Alphabet stock seems like such a safe investment, in my opinion, compared to many other high flying tech stocks trading at 50+ forward P/E ratios.  I sleep very well at night holding Alphabet in my stock portfolio.

As with every company, Google stock also has some risks.  There is a risk of government intervention on how Google collects and uses its customers data and there is a risk the government may try to break up the company which I believe is unlikely to happen.

I like to hear your discussion on stuff, but allow me to throw some critisism to the concept of DCF in particual. Yeah DCF are cool and all, but most of it is based academic jargon such as WACC and Beta. Google has 100 bill net cash, wacc is irrelevant. Beta means volatility, in finance, they believe volatility = risk. But this is just a smoke screen to make laymen think "oooh it go down it mean it bad i should sell". In reality as Buffet and the other few investors with intergrity state= Risk is the chance of permanent capital loss. This is slim with google, probably the slimmest of all companies in existence. So instead, I would just extrapolate the earnings forward and do some scenarios of market sentiment, like 15-25 pe for example, and then apply a margin of safety and then buy. Your analysis is cool, but some common sense aspects gets overlooked by doing a WACC based DCF in my opinion. Some things are inherently complicated, like quantim physics and rockets, but investing is inherently simple. No need to make it more complicated, even though the pension fund industry has thrived on this since the inception of the 401k in the US and the adoption of these concepts in Europe etc.
